    Not that it matters much any more to a retired guy, but I always sold products - including custom software - not by the technology used but by the way it addressed and solved the business challenge.

    If part of your product design is "we use/interface with a 64-bit DLL in this application," then yes, the minimum technology requirement will be for a 64-bit executable (EXE or DLL). But if it ain't... well, the 64-bit executable is not a requirement assuming the user can run 32-bit apps

    It's another thought.

  • Mr. Kevin Diggins

    #24
    29 May 2024, 07:37 PM
    Originally posted by Dan Soper View Post
    As Joe says, a 64-bit PB would be useful for interacting with 3rd-party software that has been compiled to 64 bits.
    A more common example, I think, is writing software that calls functions in a 64-bit DLL.
    Exactly right.

    A developer recently exposed me to a 64-bit DLL that enabled me to compile a local (non-internet dependent) desktop ChatGPT like program that
    uses the much touted Microsoft optimized version of Meta's LLAMA 2 Large Language Model.(Phi-3-mini-4k-instruct-q4.gguf) ~2GB in size.

    Such desktop apps are useful when you can't connect to the internet, when you are trying to protect your privacy from the internet's prying eyes
    or workiing to develop an app with integrated AI capabilities.

    Below is the small amount of BCX BASIC code needed to create the client app. (See attached screenshot)

    Code:
    GUI "Dllama_Chatbot", PIXELS

DECLARE FUNCTION LLM$ LIB "Dllama.dll" ALIAS "Dllama_Simple_Inference" (A$, B$, C$, D AS BOOLEAN, E AS UINT, X AS UCHAR, F$)

MACRO MODELNAME$ = "phi3:4B:Q4"
MACRO APPFOLDER$ = CURDIR$ ' The .exe, .dll, .gguf, and .json file -must- reside in same folder.

MACRO ENABLE (H) = EnableWindow (H, TRUE)
MACRO DISABLE (H) = EnableWindow (H, FALSE)

GLOBAL Form1 AS CONTROL
GLOBAL Edit1 AS CONTROL
GLOBAL Edit2 AS CONTROL
GLOBAL Btn1 AS CONTROL


SUB FORMLOAD
    Form1 = BCX_FORM("Dllama Chatbot built using BCX", 0, 0, 1280, 550)
    Edit1 = BCX_INPUT("List the countries with provinces", Form1, 3, 10, 20, 1250, 40) ' BCX_INPUT automatically [fires] on ENTER
    Edit2 = BCX_EDIT("The LLAMA response will appear here. Without a NVIDIA GPU, some responses can take over 2 minutes.", Form1, 2, 10, 100, 1250, 300)
    Btn1 = BCX_BUTTON("Start", Form1, 1, 575, 425, 125, 65)
    BCX_SET_FONT(Btn1, "Tahoma", 14)
    BCX_SET_FONT(Edit1, "Tahoma", 14)
    BCX_SET_FONT(Edit2, "Tahoma", 14)
    CENTER(Form1)
    SHOW(Form1)
END SUB


BEGIN EVENTS
    SELECT CASE CBMSG
      CASE WM_COMMAND

      IF CBCTL = 1 THEN
          DIM question[65535] AS CHAR
          DIM answer [65535] AS CHAR
          DIM start_time = TIMER
          BCX_SET_TEXT(Edit2, "Working ... please wait.")
          BCX_SET_TEXT(Btn1, "Working ... please wait.")
          SetFocus(Edit1)
          DISABLE(Btn1)
          DOEVENTS

         question$ = BCX_GET_TEXT$(Edit1)
         answer$ = LLM(APPFOLDER$, "models.json", MODELNAME$, FALSE, 1024, 27, question$) ' Use FALSE, if -no- NVIDIA GPU, else TRUE
         REPLACE LF$ WITH CRLF$ IN answer$ ' Convert soft returns to hard returns

         BCX_SET_TEXT(Edit2, answer$)
         BCX_SET_TEXT(Btn1, "Start")
         ENABLE(Btn1)
         DOEVENTS
         MSGBOX "Completed in " + STR$(INT(TIMER - start_time)) + " seconds", "Message"
     END IF

    END SELECT
END EVENTS
    Attached Files

    Originally posted by frank
    For more Hobby progammers it s Not necessary to have a 64 Bit Software.
    So hobbyists do not do video editing. Wrong.
    Originally posted by Michael Mattias
    But if it ain't... well, the 64-bit executable is not a requirement ...
    Doesn't follow.

    Read Eric's link to determine whether 64-bit is a requirement or not.

    In my case, it isn't.

    Having said that, my latest FreeBASIC PRNGs execute much faster with 64-bit, especially those which use a lot of Shift left/Shift right instructions. FreeBASIC's Shift left/Shift right instructions are different to PowerBASIC and have a C-like usage. In FreeBASIC we simply replace C's bitwise shifts << and >> with shl and shr.

    #31
    30 May 2024, 08:46 AM
    With the help of the static library TCLIB.LIB, you can produce 64-bit DLL (written with the free VS2022 community) that could be as small as 7 Kb.
    Converting code to 64-bit is not that hard, as long as you use direct call to the core FLAT API (No DDT encapsulation, and get rid of the deprecated CreateDialog API).

    I have written many demo projects available in both PB 32-bit and C/C++ 64-bit, and I can tell you that I am able to write smaller and faster applications in 64-bitt, using exactly the same SDK coding style syntax that has not changed since almost 30 years.

    Hello Eric, all other Guys here.. my 5 cents..
    here's a fictive Code example of Powerbasic 64

    I would buy a new issue too btw

    Code:
    #COMPILE EXE
#DIM ALL
'#include once "winapi64.inc" ' (fictive)

FUNCTION PBMAIN () AS LONG

LOCAL val1,val2,result AS LONG
val1=4
val2=6 '

'' 32 bit asm -------------------------- //
'' ! mov eax,val1
'' ! mov eax,val2 ''multiply eax by ebx
'' ! mul val1 'ebx
'' ! mov result,eax
'' 32 bit asm -------------------------- //

'' 64 bit asm fictive -------------------------- //
! mov rax, [val2]
! mul val1
! mov [result], rax
'' 64 bit asm fictive -------------------------- //

? "the result of " & STR$(val1) & " *" & STR$(val2) & " is " & STR$(result) 'return 24

LOCAL tit AS STRING
LOCAL pTit AS LONG
tit = " PowerBASIC"
pTit = STRPTR(tit)

END FUNCTION

' cause it's theoretically code example you will get with 32 bit powerbasic an error message
' Assembler variables must be declared line 19: ! mov rax,[val2]

  • Dale Yarker

    #38
    31 May 2024, 04:01 AM
    In the REM'ed out 32 bit version, why are you moving val1 to eax?

    If that line was intended to be:
    ! mov ebx, val1
    then 3rd line of 32 bit ASM is:
    ! mul ebx

    If you want 3rd line of 32 bit ASM to be:
    ! mul var1
    then that 1st line of 32 bit ASM can be removed.

    Cheers,
